Hey, y‚Äôall! Happy #WomensHistoryMonth and #TransDayOfVisibility üè≥Ô∏è‚Äç‚ößÔ∏è. I‚Äôm Elle Moxley (@elle_moxley), the founder of @MPJInstitute and an activist, director, and producer. Hi everyone! I‚Äôm Ai-jen Poo, director of the @caringacrossgen and @domesticworkers.

Thank you for letting me take over your account, Hailey, during Women‚Äôs History Month. I‚Äôm so grateful for this chance to shine a light on our nation‚Äôs 53 million family caregivers ‚Äì the nannies, house cleaners, home care workers, and family caregivers ‚Äì who care for us, for our loved ones and our homes in times of crisis and stability. 

They are mostly women and predominantly Black, Latinx, and Asian women and immigrants. And do the work that makes it possible for others ‚Äì especially women ‚Äì to go to work. Yet the sector is defined by low wages, and few benefits. Care is essential to our society, but it is undervalued.

We‚Äôve seen the devastating cost of not investing in care, on our grandparents, people with disabilities, and essential workers.

It might have taken a pandemic to see how childcare, paid leave and home and community care are essential infrastructure. But just like roads, bridges and broadband, all of us need care. That‚Äôs why we need YOU more than ever -- to win and build what matters most.

So I‚Äôm asking for your help to go beyond the quick fixes. If we want lasting racial and economic justice, our time is now for bold, permanent change. There is too much at stake for all of us, especially women of color. 

Go check out the stories to hear directly from care workers and caregivers.

Happy Women‚Äôs  History Month! My name is @ValarieKaur. I‚Äôm a civil rights leader, lawyer, faith leader, and the author of a new book called #SeeNoStranger. I am so excited for you to read my book! I share my life journey -- stories of police brutality, hate violence, sexual assault and deep healing. All along, I searched for how to change the world. Then I found it. The answer surprised me:

Revolutionary Love.

I used to roll my eyes when people said ‚Äúlove is the answer.‚Äù But the problem is not with love but with the way we talk about it. Love is not something we just feel. Love is something we DO. Love is sweet labor -- fierce, bloody, imperfect, life-giving, choice we make. When we love without limit -- love becomes revolutionary. It can change the world around us -- and inside us.

I believe Revolutionary Love is the call of our times.

Here‚Äôs why:

#1 The world is in transition. The crises we face -- the pandemic, climate disasters, assaults on our democracy, white supremacy -- are signs that our nation is in transition. The old way of being is dying. A new world wants to be born. How do we birth that world?

#2 Each of us has a role. YOU have a role. We need more than good government. We need a shift in culture and consciousness. A revolution of the heart. We can build the beloved community where we are. But only if we --

#3 Practice love -- love without limit. Revolutionary love is when we are brave enough to ‚Äúsee no stranger‚Äù -- to let everyone inside our circle of care. It is the choice to labor for others, for our opponents, and for ourselves. It‚Äôs powerful and joyful and sets us free.

Are you ready to bring revolutionary love into your life?

GO TO: VALARIEKAUR.COM.

Check out the Revolutionary Love Learning Hub! You can find videos, original music, training courses, and tools! It‚Äôs all free. We‚Äôre building a movement to practice revolutionary love together. For a deep dive, read my book. For everything you need, go to valariekaur.com.

Follow me at @valariekaur and our movement at @revloveproject.

Hey all! I‚Äôm @Luvvie Ajayi Jones, New York Times bestselling author, speaker and podcast host. I‚Äôm also co-founder of the #SharetheMicNow campaign. My purpose is to use my words to make people feel joy, think critically, and compel them to take action that leaves this world better than they found it. My superpower is my side-eye and my love language is shoes.
 
I‚Äôm the author of the newly released book @ProfessionalTroublemaker: The Fear-Fighter Manual, which aims to loan you courage in the moments when you‚Äôre asked to do something big or scary. It‚Äôs especially relevant right now, because it‚Äôs Women‚Äôs History Month. This year‚Äôs theme is #ChoosetoChallenge, which asks us to commit to speaking up when it is necessary. My book gives you the tools to do that. To be a #ProfessionalTroublemaker in this world, it means you‚Äôre challenging systems, ideas and people that aren‚Äôt just. Your voice is necessary.
 
So today, I‚Äôm excited to take over Hailey‚Äôs platform. Now, let‚Äôs talk about why it‚Äôs important for us to make good trouble (word to the late, great John Lewis). Meet me in her IG Stories.

Today‚Äôs takeover is Amanda NguyeÃÇÃÉn!

Hi there. Today, you might feel scared. I know what it feels like to be scared. My name is @amandangocnguyen and after my rape, I felt despair. But I also felt fire. So when I met a broken criminal justice system -- like so many survivors whose rape kits have been destroyed without notice -- I rewrote the law. Together, with my team at @risenow.us , we organized and did the impossible -- passed the Survivors‚Äô Bill of Rights unanimously through the United States Congress.

I wrote it as a matter of survival. If that bill could speak, it would scream. It would sing from the pages. It would light itself on fire. It represents the endless pursuit of a more perfect world. This is what I did with my fire. What will you do with yours?

There is a long, rich tradition of activism in the world‚Äîof people taking their painful living truths and channeling them into justice.  I chose to join that tradition by penning my own civil rights into existence. Now, I‚Äôm helping others pen their own civil rights into existence, too. From combating anti-asian hate crimes, to voting rights, to women‚Äôs rights - at Rise we‚Äôre putting democracy back into your hands. I‚Äôm proud to say we‚Äôve passed 33 laws for 85  million people. But the work isn‚Äôt done. 

The world is going through a moment of reckoning now. The people who have the solutions to the world‚Äôs most pressing problems are the people that live the problem every day. Know that your voice matters. Community organizing matters. No one is powerless when we come together. No one can make us invisible when we demand to be seen. If you want to support our civil rights activists you can give at risenow.us/donate.

Today‚Äôs takeover is Oge Egbuonu!:

Hey y'all, my name is Oge (@ogetheyogi) and I am an artist, activist and the filmmaker of @invisibleportraits 
 
(In)Visible Portraits is an offering, a meditation and love letter to the power in each of our stories and a reminder to Black women and girls, that our story does not end in defeat but rather victory and as re-education to everyone else. 
 
This poetic documentary explores the historical oppression of Black Women in America by unveiling the history of how we got here, dismantling the false framework of the present-day reality, and celebrating the heritage of Black Women to inspire the next generation. 
 
(In)Visible Portraits is also a call to action, to remembering and to revealing a fuller truth about the experience of Black women in America. 
 
My hope is that if I tell stories well, people will leave asking themselves better questions and as a result they will do the internal and external work that's necessary in creating a world that is equitable, fair and justice...one that holds reverence for all the contributions Black women have made and continue to do. I believe you can show someone spirituality, or you can show someone creativity, either way is fine...they are both going to spiritually awaken the person if done correctly. 
 
Tonight, we are creating sacred space and connecting across the country by watching the premiere on @owntv at 8pmCST/9pEST/9pPST

I'm @desmondmeade44, the Executive Director of @flrightsrestore, a grassroots organization dedicated to ending the disenfranchisement and discrimination against returning citizens (people with previous felony convictions). 

Did you know that before the passage of Amendment 4 in 2018, over 1.4 million Americans living in Florida were permanently banned from voting? 

Amendment 4 granted the restoration of voting rights to all returning citizens after completing their sentence, excluding convictions for murder and sexual assault.

Even after 66% of Floridians voted to pass Amendment 4, Florida's legislators ignored the will of the people, creating more financial barriers. These democracy deniers forced poor people to choose between feeding their families or paying for the right to vote. 

Where other people see obstacles, we see opportunities. Through our advocacy work in 2020, we raised more than $27 million to pay the fines and fees of over 40,000 returning citizens. 

Our work to protect voting rights is essential to the safety and improvement of our state and nation. We are an organization that believes in second chances and that every American has the power to be a change agent in their community.

Today, there are still 700,000 people who owe outstanding fines and fees and cannot participate in democracy. So, how can you join our movement? 
Follow FRRC @FlRightsRestore to get involved in our work.
Donate to our Fines and Fees Fund.
Use the hashtag #letmypeoplevote and show us how you're pledging to put people over politics.

Today‚Äôs takeover is @ucheblackstockmd!: 

Hi everyone, I‚Äôm @ucheblackstockmd. I‚Äôm a physician and thought leader on bias and racism in health care. I‚Äôm also the Founder and CEO of Advancing Health Equity, which I created to partner with healthcare organizations to dismantle bias and racism in healthcare and to close the gap in racial health inequities.

I‚Äôm excited about this opportunity to interact with you all. The COVID-19 pandemic has  revealed profound racial health inequities as Black, Latinx and Indigenous communities have been the hardest-hit by the pandemic.

This is due to multiple factors including lack of access to health care, more likely to be burdened with chronic diseases, more likely to be restricted essential or service worker jobs and more likely to take public transportation. These factors are called the social determinants of health and systemic racism ties all of these factors together.

You can make a difference by educating yourselves about how systemic racism influences health outcomes, through practices and policies, like redlining and predatory mortgage lending, and have led to the deep racial health inequities that we see today. An individual‚Äôs zip code is a better predictor of health outcomes than their genetic code. Look around in your own communities to see how you can make a difference by working in a food bank, or an organization that helps connect people with affordable housing, or mentoring a child.

 #healthequity #healthcare #racism #racialhealthinequities #socialdeterminantsofhealth

Happy #BlackHistoryMonth!¬†

I‚Äôm @Baratunde Thurston, and I host a podcast called @HowToCitizenwithBaratunde.

Black people have long been denied the rights of full citizenship, and yet we have shown up consistently, and contributed to the growth of this nation, often demonstrating the highest levels of loyalty and patriotism. 

I‚Äôm addressing a U.S. context, though this has been true in many nations around the world.¬†At our show, we think of ‚Äúcitizen‚Äù as a verb, not as a legal status. It‚Äôs open to participation by all.

If you can vote, please continue to do it, but whether you can or not there's more to it. For our democracy to work, we have to work for our democracy. I know that can feel overwhelming or confusing, but the good news is that we're here to help.¬†

We tell the stories of people CITIZENING in amazing ways, and we give you actions you can take (other than screaming into your pillow at the news). You're not alone. Listen to the podcast. Sign up for emails or texts at howtocitizen.com. Let's citizen together.

I would say my most favorite part of existing is human connection. I absolutely love connecting with other people, I love finding common interests between me and others, hearing people‚Äôs story, I love laughing with others, and I love crying with others. I feel so very very deeply. My heart explodes with happiness when my friends and family are happy and my heart feels crushed when they are hurting and sad. The reason I say all of this is: because I love to connect, I do my best to expose my heart which means I love freely and I empathize deeply, and because of that I also hurt very easily when I feel like people don‚Äôt see my heart and see me for who I am and the reason I‚Äôm even sharing this, is because Instagram, Twitter etc is SUCH a breeding ground for cruelty towards each other, and because people don‚Äôt take the time to connect with each other on an honest level before they resort to hatred, it starts to damage what could be really beautiful human interaction and connection. I could sit here all day and say the hate doesn‚Äôt bug me, that the words that are said don‚Äôt affect me. But NEWS FLASH: it hurts to be torn apart on the internet!!! It hurts to be compared to other human beings every single day, it hurts for people to jump to conclusions and make assumptions. It hurts to be called names, and to feel like you don‚Äôt measure up to a certain  standard.. the list goes on and on. I share this only because it weighs often on my heart and because it‚Äôs important to be honest about how these things affect us mentally and emotionally. Hopefully it speaks to someone struggling with the same. 
with that being said Happy New Year. Let‚Äôs connect more in 2020 :)

Today is World Mental Health day, and it‚Äôs an opportunity for us to open up more conversations for change and prevention. In some way or another we all struggle, and everyone deserves to be supported when they are struggling. Sadly, there is still such a stigma around mental health. So many people don‚Äôt feel supported and don‚Äôt feel as though they have the strength to ask for help, and when we feel hopeless and helpless it can lead to a devastating result. So it's important that on #WorldMentalHealthDay we come forward and talk about these issues,¬†and we remind each other that it's okay not to be okay. Let‚Äôs openly change the conversation and help each other feel safe enough to talk about our struggles, our issues, our fears and our demons. Let‚Äôs be there for one another EVERYDAY!! NOT JUST TODAY!!! and love each other, be there for one another through it. Today, we share resources from amazing organizations like @crisistextline and @active_minds who are helping to change the conversation for those who are hurting and feel hopeless. Today, in a world filled with so much hate and devastation let‚Äôs choose to spread empathy and kindness, because our world needs so much more of that and it starts with us showing it to one another..

stepping into 2019 I want to be more open, I want to be more open about the things I struggle with, and be able to be more vulnerable. I‚Äôm a 22 years old, and the truth is no matter how amazing life may look from the outside I struggle...

I have had more days than I can count where I‚Äôve found myself scrolling through Instagram comparing myself, comparing my looks, feeling like I‚Äôm not good enough feeling like I lack so many things and really struggling to be confident in who I am because I constantly feel like I‚Äôm just not good enough. Every single day is a confidence battle for me. I‚Äôm not writing this for a pity party or for sympathy but just to simply say, I‚Äôm a human.. I‚Äôm a young woman, I‚Äôm learning who I am and, it‚Äôs REALLY FREAKING HARD. It‚Äôs hard finding who you are, but what‚Äôs even harder is being picked apart and compared to other women while trying to do that. There are days that I‚Äôm simply broken because of it. It would be incredible if other young girls and women could find it in themselves to lift each other up, to stop making other women who are struggling JUST LIKE THEM, feel incompetent and less than. What I do know is, God made us individuals for a reason, with our own beauty, our own personalities, and our own story because there‚Äôs a specific plan and purpose for each and every human created and he makes no mistakes!! So this year I‚Äôm gonna do my very best to just be ME and be confident with who I am. Cause I am enough, and I‚Äôm loved, and you are enough and you‚Äôre loved.
